notes.text:
Updated samba4 packages that fix one security issue are now available for
Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6.

The Red Hat Security Response Team has rated this update as having
Important security impact. A Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS)
base score, which gives a detailed severity rating, is available from the
CVE link in the References section.
notes.title: Topic

notes.text:
Samba is an open-source implementation of the Server Message Block (SMB) or
Common Internet File System (CIFS) protocol, which allows PC-compatible
machines to share files, printers, and other information.

A heap-based buffer overflow flaw was found in Samba's NetBIOS message
block daemon (nmbd). An attacker on the local network could use this flaw
to send specially crafted packets that, when processed by nmbd, could
possibly lead to arbitrary code execution with root privileges.
(CVE-2014-3560)

All Samba users are advised to upgrade to these updated packages, which
contain a backported patch to correct this issue. After installing this
update, the smb service will be restarted automatically.

cwe.name: Insertion of Sensitive Information Into Sent Data

notes.text: A flaw was found in the way Samba created responses for certain authenticated client requests when a shadow-copy VFS module was enabled. An attacker able to send an authenticated request could use this flaw to disclose limited portions of memory per each request.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: This issue does not affect the version of samba as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5 and 6. This issue does not affect the version of samba3x as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5. This issue affects the version of samba4 as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6. The Red Hat Security Response Team has rated this issue as having Low security impact, a future update may address this flaw.
notes.title: Statement

notes.text: The CVSS score(s) listed for this vulnerability do not reflect the associated product's status, and are included for informational purposes to better understand the severity of this vulnerability.

notes.text: A denial of service flaw was found in the way the sys_recvfile() function of nmbd, the NetBIOS message block daemon, processed non-blocking sockets. An attacker could send a specially crafted packet that, when processed, would cause nmbd to enter an infinite loop and consume an excessive amount of CPU time.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: It was discovered that smbd, the Samba file server daemon, did not properly handle certain files that were stored on the disk and used a valid Unicode character in the file name. An attacker able to send an authenticated non-Unicode request that attempted to read such a file could cause smbd to crash.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: samba: smbd unicode path names denial of service
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: This issue affects the versions of samba3x as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5. This issue affects the versions of samba and samba4 as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6. This issue affects the versions of samba as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7. This issue did not affect the versions of samba as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5.

cwe.name: Improper Restriction of Operations within the Bounds of a Memory Buffer

notes.text: A heap-based buffer overflow flaw was found in Samba's NetBIOS message block daemon (nmbd). An attacker on the local network could use this flaw to send specially crafted packets that, when processed by nmbd, could possibly lead to arbitrary code execution with root privileges.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: samba: remote code execution in nmbd
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: This issue did not affect the versions of samba or samba3x as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 5, and the versions of samba as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6, as it only affected Samba 4.0.0 and higher.
